Manitou Springs Education Foundation (MSEF)
August 27 at 9:30 AM ·

Give to the Manitou Cares Campaign and help make dreams like this one possible! https://msef4kids.org/donate/

We're raising money to support the teachers and staff of Manitou School District in this challenging time for education. The funds will directly support teachers and staff, empowering them to do things like:
• Buy instruments for an after-school rock band
• Purchase materials for yoga or mindfulness
• Build a sensory corner to encourage self-regulation

Our goal is to bring hope and joy to our teachers and staff by ensuring that there is still support for new and ongoing extracurricular projects that lift our educator’s spirits while serving our children.

Manitou Springs Education Foundation is a designated 501(c)(3) mission-based organization.

post_text:
You may be eligible to receive $279 per child to help feed your family since schools were closed due to COVID-19. Pandemic EBT, or P-EBT, is a new beneﬁt for families that usually receive free and reduced-price school meals. These P-EBT funds can be used to purchase food at stores that accept EBT.

Most families who currently receive SNAP benefits will see these funds automatically added to their accounts and no further action is needed.

Other families will need to complete a simple and quick online application in order to receive P-EBT. To complete this application, you must receive a state-issued student ID, or SASID, from Manitou Springs School District 14. https://www.colorado.gov/cdhs/p-ebt

Please contact Paula Faucette (Director of Nutrition Services) at pfaucette@mssd14.org or call 719-685-2000 for more information about P-EBT and to receive your student ID.

post_text: We would like to make you aware of an initiative within the Pikes Peak Region to honor the graduating class of 2020. The goal is to turn on the lights in as many buildings, businesses and homes across our region for one hour on May 20, 2020 beginning at 8:20 p.m. (2020 military time) to give a symbolic yet visible display of support for our (and really, your) local graduating seniors, and to let them know the entire city is cheering them on to the finish line. Residents, businesses and organizations are then encouraged to post a photo or video of their unique and visible light source (porchlights, exterior lighting, fleet vehicles, large-scale buildings, holiday lighting, lanterns – the more creative and visible the better!) to social media on May 20 with a congratulatory message for graduates. #BeTheLightMSSD City of Manitou Springs

It is important to focus on the positive ways our students, families, and staff are connecting and experiencing this time of transition. There are countless stories and examples. I wanted to share this particular moment with our community.

The mother of this 1st Grader at MSES gave us permission to share this video with everyone.

Each morning, before she begins her remote learning with her teacher (Ms. Carter), she watches this video (of Andy Grammer's "Don't Give Up On Me" ft. PS22 Chorus) in the presence of her mom. Her positive approach to the day is a powerful example of how a wise child makes the best of the moment.

We hope that every child is able to find meaningful ways to stay connected because we're "not givin' up."

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4-GPPMDMQ8U&feature=youtu.be

Our Manitou Springs School District Community has really pulled together to consider how we can continue to work together to support students. You can access our website: https://www.mssd14.org/remote_learning for more information.

I am so proud to work alongside such caring and dedicated professionals who care so deeply about our students, families, and each other.

Also, thank you to the many parents and community members who have volunteered to support in amazing ways.

All of our staff are planning some really creative and thoughtful ways to stay connected during this time period. We know that some strategies will work better than other strategies, but we look forward to learning along the way. This is one more way will always be better together.

The video below is one example:

https://photos.app.goo.gl/ig5DMSoWCVSXYscF7

We also want to say "Thank you" to all veterans.

We would like to thank everyone for their support through this event. Traffic and parking has returned to normal. Transportation services will resume approximately 2 hours later than the normal pickup time. For example, if your child is typically picked up at 7:05 am, the bus will arrive 9:05 am.

School will begin at 10:05 am. Students may start arriving at 9:35 am.

If you choose to keep your child home today for the remainder of the day, please notify the Attendance Office at the Middle or High School.

post_text:
At Manitou Springs School District, our top priority is to have a safe and productive learning environment for students and staff.

This evening, we have been working closely with the City of Manitou Springs. In reviewing protests in Colorado Springs, we have decided that we will be on a 2-hour delay Monday, October 14. This only pertains to Middle and High School students. Busses will pick-up students 2-hours later than the usual pick-up time. For example, if your child is typically picked up at 7:00 am. Your child will be picked up at 9:00 am.

School will begin at 10:05 am. Students may start arriving at 9:35 am.

We will let you know if any changes are made to this start time. If you choose to keep your child home tomorrow, please notify the Attendance Office at the Middle or High School.

Thank you so much for working with us on this.
